<main role="main">
<article>
Here is an AI-resistant assessment for the "Rhetorical Strategies in Persuasive Speeches" lesson:</p><p>---</p><p><h2>🗣️ Rhetorical Strategies in Action: Analyzing Persuasion in Our Community</h2></p><p>**Subject:** English Language Arts<br>**Grade Level:** 10th Grade<br>**Lesson Title:** Rhetorical Strategies in Persuasive Speeches<br>**Learning Objectives:**<br>  - Define and distinguish between ethos, pathos, and logos as rhetorical strategies<br>  - Identify examples of each rhetorical appeal in authentic persuasive texts<br>  - Analyze how speakers combine rhetorical strategies to achieve their purpose<br>  - Evaluate the effectiveness of rhetorical choices in context</p><p>---</p><p><h3>📝 Assessment Overview</h3></p><p>This assessment challenges you to apply your understanding of rhetorical strategies by analyzing a real-world persuasive message within our community. You will demonstrate your analytical skills, track your thinking process, and reflect on the choices made by a speaker. The focus is on *how* you engage with the material and *your unique observations*, not just a final "correct" answer.</p><p>---</p><p><h3>💡 AI Policy: Limited Assist 🤖</h3></p><p>You may use AI tools (like ChatGPT, Bard, etc.) for **brainstorming ideas or generating initial concepts ONLY.** For example, you could ask an AI, "What are some common places to hear persuasive speeches in a community?" or "Give me examples of pathos in a commercial." However, all analysis, identification of strategies, direct quotes, and reflections must be your own original work based on your personal engagement with the chosen persuasive message. Do NOT use AI to draft your analysis, identify specific examples, or write any part of your reflection.</p><p>---</p><p><h3>🎯 Instructions:</h3></p><p><li> **Select a Persuasive Message:** Identify a live or recorded persuasive message directed at the Minneapolis community from the last month. This could be:</li><br>    *   A speech given by a school administrator at North High School (e.g., during an assembly, an announcement, or recorded message).<br>    *   A portion of a City Council meeting or school board meeting (available online via City of Minneapolis or Minneapolis Public Schools websites).<br>    *   A local news broadcast segment where someone is advocating for a cause in Minneapolis.<br>    *   An advertisement from a local Minneapolis business or non-profit with a strong persuasive element.<br>    *   A public address by a student leader at North High School during a school event.</p><p>    *You must choose a message that you can access and re-watch/re-read multiple times.*</p><p><li> **Analyze the Rhetoric:** As you watch/read your chosen message, identify and analyze the use of ethos, pathos, and logos.</li></p><p>---</p><p><h3>🕵️‍♀️ Process Checkpoints (Submit as you work)</h3></p><p>**Checkpoint 1: Initial Observation & Selection** (Due: End of Day 2 of the unit)</p><p><li> **What persuasive speech or message have you tentatively chosen for your analysis?** Be specific (e.g., "Principal Smith's address during the North High School 'Spirit Week Kickoff' assembly on October 18th" or "The City Council meeting segment from October 25th regarding funding for local parks, specifically Council Member Johnson's remarks"). Even if it's tentative, state your current choice.</li><br><li> **Why did this particular message catch your attention as potentially rich for rhetorical analysis?** (Think broadly: Was it the topic? The speaker? A feeling it evoked? Its relevance to North High School or Minneapolis?)</li><br><li> **Jot down 2-3 specific phrases or moments from your chosen message that immediately stood out to you.** You don't need to analyze them yet, just note them down.</li></p><p>**Checkpoint 2: First Pass - Identifying Potential Appeals** (Due: End of Day 4 of the unit)</p><p><li> **Focus on *one* rhetorical appeal (ethos, pathos, or logos) that you think is most prominent in your chosen persuasive message.** Why do you believe this appeal is the most emphasized by the speaker?</li><br><li> **From your chosen message, identify two distinct moments or statements that you believe exemplify this prominent appeal.** For each moment, copy the exact quote or describe the specific action/tone if it's non-verbal, and briefly explain *why* you think it fits that appeal (e.g., "This is pathos because it uses vivid language to describe the suffering of local families").</li><br><li> **What is *one specific question* you have about distinguishing between ethos, pathos, and logos after this first analytical attempt?** What is confusing you? (e.g., "How is X statement logos and not just a fact?")</li></p><p>**Checkpoint 3: Deeper Dive - Challenging Assumptions** (Due: End of Day 6 of the unit)</p><p><li> **Revisit one of the statements or moments you analyzed in Checkpoint 2.** Could that same statement/moment also be interpreted as a different rhetorical appeal? If so, explain how and why. If not, explain why it exclusively fits your original classification.</li><br><li> **Identify a moment in your chosen message where the speaker *could have* used a stronger rhetorical appeal but didn't, or where an appeal seemed to fall flat.** Describe the moment and explain which appeal they missed and what they might have done differently to make it more effective for the North High School community or Minneapolis audience.</li><br><li> **Based on your current analysis, what do you believe is the speaker's primary purpose in this message?** How do you think they are attempting to achieve it through their use of rhetoric?</li></p><p>---</p><p><h3>📸 Artifact Requirement: Annotated Transcript/Screenshot</h3></p><p>**Artifact:** A physical print-out or clearly annotated digital screenshot (if the message is visual) of a key section (minimum 200 words or 60 seconds of video annotated with time stamps and descriptions) from your chosen persuasive message.</p><p>**What to include:**<br><li>  Clearly mark and label at least **one example of ethos, one of pathos, and one of logos** within your chosen section. Use different colored highlighters or text boxes, and draw arrows to specific words, phrases, or visual elements (if applicable).</li><br><li>  For each labeled example, provide a concise, handwritten or typed note explaining *why* it's an example of that specific rhetorical appeal *and* how it contributes to the speaker's overall purpose for their Minneapolis audience.</li><br><li>  Include the full citation of your chosen persuasive message (speaker, date, context, link if applicable).</li></p><p>**Why this is AI-resistant:** AI can generate rhetorical analyses, but it cannot authentically highlight specific portions of a physically existing document (like a transcript from a live local event) or screenshot of a locally contextualized video, nor can it provide your personal, hand-drawn annotations or specific, local connections. This artifact proves you engaged directly with the material.</p><p>---</p><p><h3>🤔 Reflection Prompt</h3></p><p>After immersing yourself in this persuasive message and dissecting its rhetorical components, consider the following:</p><p>"Reflect on a moment during this assessment where your initial understanding of ethos, pathos, or logos was challenged or deepened by what you observed in your chosen Minneapolis-based persuasive message. Describe the specific moment or example from the message that caused this shift in your thinking. How did analyzing a real-world, locally relevant message change your perspective on how these appeals actually work, compared to just reading definitions in a textbook?"</p><p>---</p><p><h3>🤖 AI Disclosure</h3></p><p><li> Did you use any AI tools (e.g., ChatGPT, Bard, Copilot) during any stage of this assessment?</li><br>    *   Yes / No<br><li> If yes, specifically describe how you used the AI tool(s). Provide exact prompts you used and explain the brainstorming assistance you received.</li><br><li> Confirm that all analysis, identification of specific rhetorical examples, direct quotes, and personal reflections included in this assessment are entirely your own original work, developed without AI generation or drafting.</li></p><p>---
</article>
</main>
</body>
